   =20
      OpenAI ownership
   =20
 =20

The normal way to own a share of a company=E2=80=99s profits is to buy its =
stock. If you find a company that you think is promising, and you want to g=
ive it some money to finance its operations in exchange for a share of its =
profits, you might buy, say,=C2=A010% of its stock, and then in some rough =
sense you own 10% of its future profits. Not in any very strict sense =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the company gets=C2=A0the profits, and may or may not pay some =
or all of them out to you as dividends=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but people do te=
nd to think of a share of stock as a share in future profits.
But while stock is the=C2=A0standard=C2=A0way to buy a share of a company=
=E2=80=99s profits, it is not the only way. Here=E2=80=99s another one:=C2=
=A0I=C2=A0buy 10% of the company=E2=80=99s stock, and then I write you a to=
tal return swap, a derivative contract saying that I=E2=80=99ll pay you $1 =
for every $1 that the stock goes up (and you=E2=80=99ll pay me $1 for every=
 $1 it goes down). That way, you have economic exposure to the stock: You m=
ake money if it goes up=C2=A0and lose money if it goes down. But you don=E2=
=80=99t own the actual shares of stock, or some of the rights that attach t=
o them. (You normally can=E2=80=99t vote for directors, for instance.) You =
have economic ownership of the stock, but you don=E2=80=99t actually own st=
ock.
  [1]

There are other ways. Many crypto tokens, for instance, are kind of=C2=A0pr=
ofit interests in some project.
  [2]
=C2=A0Or more simply, you=C2=A0go to the company and say =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=
=80=99d like to buy 10% of your profits=E2=80=9D and the company says =E2=
=80=9Csure=E2=80=9D and writes a contract saying =E2=80=9Cyou are entitled =
to 10% of our profits.=E2=80=9D And then when the company has profits it wr=
ites you a quarterly check.
  [3]

Why would you do any of these things, instead of buying stock? Here are thr=
ee possible answers:
=09You arrived from Mars 10 minutes ago,=C2=A0you have never heard of =E2=
=80=9Ccommon stock,=E2=80=9D so you reason from first principles about how =
to invest in a company and take a share of its profits. =E2=80=9CWhat if we=
 wrote some sort of a contract giving me a share of the profits,=E2=80=9D y=
ou say, etc.=C2=A0=09The company is not actually a company and doesn=E2=80=
=99t have stock, so you need to resort to workarounds. You want to give mon=
ey to a university lab, or a government project, or a nonprofit organizatio=
n, or your brother-in-law,=C2=A0to develop some commercial thing, and in ex=
change you want 10% of the commercial thing=E2=80=99s profits. Maybe you wr=
ite a profit-sharing contract. Or you want to invest money in a decentraliz=
ed crypto project, and you take back tokens=C2=A0that seem likely to go up =
if it succeeds.=09Regulatory arbitrage. Because stock is the normal way to =
own a share of a company=E2=80=99s profits, a lot of=C2=A0rules=C2=A0apply =
to stock, and if you buy something that is Not Stock you might avoid those =
rules, while still getting the benefits (profit sharing, etc.) of stock. Fo=
r instance, the US Securities and Exchange Commission has a lot of disclosu=
re and other rules that apply to people who buy   more than 5% of a public =
company=E2=80=99s stock; some investors want to avoid those disclosure rule=
s for various reasons, so they will use total return swaps or other derivat=
ives rather than buying stock directly. (There is a cat-and-mouse element t=
o this, where people use swaps to avoid the rules, so the SEC   revises the=
 rules to capture swaps.)=C2=A0Or there are margin rules limiting how much =
money you can borrow=C2=A0to buy stocks, while the rules for derivatives ca=
n be laxer. (This is part of what went wrong with   Archegos Capital Manage=
ment.)=C2=A0Or US antitrust law  requires regulatory preapproval for anyone=
 buying more than a certain amount of a company=E2=80=99s stock; buying Not=
 Stock can avoid those rules too.=C2=A0

Reason 1 is fun but, I think, rarely applies.
  [4]
=C2=A0But we have   talked a   lot   recently about the drama and corporate=
 structure of OpenAI, which is technically a nonprofit, but which has taken=
 billions of dollars from Microsoft Corp. and other investors in exchange f=
or (capped) participation in the profits of its for-profit (uh,  capped-pro=
fit) subsidiary. Basically OpenAI=E2=80=99s strategy is to take Microsoft=
=E2=80=99s money, use it to build chatbots and other sort-of-artificial-int=
elligence tools, make many billions of dollars from the chatbots, use some =
of the money to pay Microsoft a lavish return on its investment, use the re=
st to build artificial general intelligence, and then use artificial genera=
l intelligence =E2=80=9Cfor the benefit of humanity,=E2=80=9D rather than f=
or the benefit of Microsoft.
OpenAI seems to be   worth $86 billion, and I have=C2=A0joked that =E2=80=
=9Cas far as I can tell no one in human history has ever purchased shares i=
n a nonprofit at an $86 billion valuation,=E2=80=9D but that was just a sho=
rthand, and Microsoft=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0purchase shares in OpenAI, o=
r not exactly.
  [5]
=C2=A0It bought a capped profit interest in OpenAI=E2=80=99s capped-profit =
subsidiary?
Part of this is for Reason 2: OpenAI is a nonprofit, it has unusual goals, =
and it is pursuing those goals with an unusual profit-sharing mechanism rat=
her than with normal stock.
But part of it is for Reason 3, regulatory arbitrage.   Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=
 Dina Bass and Leah Nylen report:

With global regulators examining Microsoft Corp.=E2=80=99s $13 billion inve=
stment in OpenAI, the software giant has a simple argument it hopes will re=
sonate with antitrust officials: It doesn=E2=80=99t own a traditional stake=
 in the buzzy startup so can=E2=80=99t be said to control it.
When Microsoft negotiated an additional $10 billion investment in OpenAI in=
 January, it opted for an unusual arrangement, people familiar with the mat=
ter said at the time. Rather than buy a chunk of the cutting-edge artificia=
l intelligence lab, it cut a deal to receive almost half of OpenAI=E2=80=99=
s financial returns until the investment is repaid up to a pre-determined c=
ap, one of the people said. The unorthodox structure was concocted because =
OpenAI is a capped for-profit company housed inside a non-profit organizati=
on.
It=E2=80=99s not clear regulators see a distinction, however. On Friday the=
 UK Competition and Markets Authority said it was gathering information fro=
m stakeholders to determine whether the collaboration between the two firms=
 threatens competition in the UK, home of Google=E2=80=99s AI research lab =
Deepmind. The US Federal Trade Commission is also examining the nature of M=
icrosoft=E2=80=99s investment in OpenAI and whether it may violate antitrus=
t laws, according to a person familiar with the matter. =E2=80=A6
Microsoft didn=E2=80=99t report the transaction to the agency because the i=
nvestment in OpenAI doesn=E2=80=99t amount to control of the company under =
US law, the person said. OpenAI is a non-profit and acquisitions of non-cor=
porate entities aren=E2=80=99t reported under US merger law, regardless of =
value. Agency officials are analyzing the situation and assessing what its =
options are.
=E2=80=9CWhile details of our agreement remain confidential, it is importan=
t to note that Microsoft does not own any portion of OpenAI and is simply e=
ntitled to a share of profit distributions,=E2=80=9D a Microsoft spokespers=
on said in a statement.=C2=A0

Sure. Ownership of a company consists=C2=A0mainly=C2=A0of being entitled to=
 a share of profit distributions, but not=C2=A0only=C2=A0that; ownership do=
es often (not always) come with, for instance, voting rights. Microsoft has=
 isolated the profit share and taken only that, not actual ownership. Okay =
fine and also a  board observer seat.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not clear regulators see a distinction,=E2=80=9D or t=
hat they should really. The conceptual overlap between =E2=80=9Cowning a po=
rtion of OpenAI=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cbeing entitled to a share of profit d=
istributions=E2=80=9D is not perfect, but it is large, and a regulator migh=
t reasonably say =E2=80=9Cclose enough.=E2=80=9D
Also here is a small fun fact about this distinction. When I   wrote about =
OpenAI last month, I included this organizational chart from its own websit=
e:


   =20

I clipped that chart from the website myself, on Nov. 19, though=C2=A0I cir=
cled =E2=80=9CMinority owner=E2=80=9D in blue for this post.=C2=A0I went ba=
ck to  the website yesterday to check, and found this=C2=A0slightly differe=
nt=C2=A0chart:


   =20

See the difference? Again, I took the liberty of circling it in blue. I do =
not know the details of Microsoft=E2=80=99s contractual arrangement with Op=
enAI, or if they have changed since November. But in November, OpenAI=E2=80=
=99s website said that Microsoft was a =E2=80=9Cminority owner=E2=80=9D of =
its capped-profit subsidiary. In December, when =E2=80=9Cit is important to=
 note that Microsoft does not own any portion of OpenAI,=E2=80=9D the websi=
te says it has a =E2=80=9Cminority economic interest.=E2=80=9D You can see =
how people might confuse those things, since OpenAI did.
One other thing I should say is that  here is a claim that OpenAI=E2=80=99s=
 employees=C2=A0get a capped profit interest instead of stock (or stock opt=
ions, or restricted stock units), because of its nonprofit structure, and t=
hat this profit interest gets better=C2=A0tax treatment, for them, than sta=
ndard startup equity awards:

People receiving profit interests will be granted the units upon their vest=
ing date at no additional cost. Because of that, there=E2=80=99s an additio=
nal key tax benefit in that they are tax-free upon issuance and vesting, so=
 the only tax hit would be a capital gains tax when the profit is received =
or sold.
In contrast, with a traditional Restricted Stock Unit (RSU) that you=E2=80=
=99d see at a MAANG level company, when the RSU vests, an employee will be =
taxed upon receiving their RSUs immediately. This is because the RSU is ess=
entially a percentage of equity in the company and holds a value at whateve=
r the market rate is for that company=E2=80=99s stock.

Regulatory arbitrage everywhere!

