<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The normal way to own a share of a company=E2=
=80=99s profits is to buy its stock. If you find a company that you think i=
s promising, and you want to give it some money to finance its operations i=
n exchange for a share of its profits, you might buy, say,=C2=A010% of its =
stock, and then in some rough sense you own 10% of its future profits. Not =
in any very strict sense =E2=80=94=C2=A0the company gets=C2=A0the profits, =
and may or may not pay some or all of them out to you as dividends=C2=A0=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but people do tend to think of a share of stock as a share in f=
uture profits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But while stock is the=C2=A0<em>standard=C2=A0=
</em>way to buy a share of a company=E2=80=99s profits, it is not the only =
way. Here=E2=80=99s another one:=C2=A0<em>I=C2=A0</em>buy 10% of the compan=
y=E2=80=99s stock, and then I write you a total return swap, a derivative c=
ontract saying that I=E2=80=99ll pay you $1 for every $1 that the stock goe=
s up (and you=E2=80=99ll pay me $1 for every $1 it goes down). That way, yo=
u have economic exposure to the stock: You make money if it goes up=C2=A0an=
d lose money if it goes down. But you don=E2=80=99t own the actual shares o=
f stock, or some of the rights that attach to them. (You normally can=E2=80=
=99t vote for directors, for instance.) You have economic ownership of the =
stock, but you don=E2=80=99t actually own stock.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are other ways. Many crypto tokens, for =
instance, are <em>kind of=C2=A0</em>profit interests in some project.<a cla=
ss=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent=
 !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Or more simply, you=C2=A0go to the company and say =E2=80=9Chey I=
=E2=80=99d like to buy 10% of your profits=E2=80=9D and the company says =
=E2=80=9Csure=E2=80=9D and writes a contract saying =E2=80=9Cyou are entitl=
ed to 10% of our profits.=E2=80=9D And then when the company has profits it=
 writes you a quarterly check.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote=
-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impo=
rtant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why would you do any of these things, instead =
of buying stock? Here are three possible answers:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You arrived from Mars 10 minutes ago,=
=C2=A0you have never heard of =E2=80=9Ccommon stock,=E2=80=9D so you reason=
 from first principles about how to invest in a company and take a share of=
 its profits. =E2=80=9CWhat if we wrote some sort of a contract giving me a=
 share of the profits,=E2=80=9D you say, etc.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">The company is not actually a company and doesn=E2=80=99t=
 have stock, so you need to resort to workarounds. You want to give money t=
o a university lab, or a government project, or a nonprofit organization, o=
r your brother-in-law,=C2=A0to develop some commercial thing, and in exchan=
ge you want 10% of the commercial thing=E2=80=99s profits. Maybe you write =
a profit-sharing contract. Or you want to invest money in a decentralized c=
rypto project, and you take back tokens=C2=A0that seem likely to go up if i=
t succeeds.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Regulatory arbitrage. =
Because stock is the normal way to own a share of a company=E2=80=99s profi=
ts, a lot of=C2=A0<em>rules=C2=A0</em>apply to stock, and if you buy someth=
ing that is Not Stock you might avoid those rules, while still getting the =
benefits (profit sharing, etc.) of stock. For instance, the US Securities a=
nd Exchange Commission has a lot of disclosure and other rules that apply t=
