</div><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See the difference? Again, I took the li=
berty of circling it in blue. I do not know the details of Microsoft=E2=80=
=99s contractual arrangement with OpenAI, or if they have changed since Nov=
ember. But in November, OpenAI=E2=80=99s website said that Microsoft was a =
=E2=80=9Cminority owner=E2=80=9D of its capped-profit subsidiary. In Decemb=
er, when =E2=80=9Cit is important to note that Microsoft does not own any p=
ortion of OpenAI,=E2=80=9D the website says it has a =E2=80=9Cminority econ=
omic interest.=E2=80=9D You can see how people might confuse those things, =
since OpenAI did.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One other thing I should say is that <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33655342.286402/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cubGV2ZWxzLmZ5aS9ibG9nL29wZW5haS1jb21wZW5zYXRpb24uaHRtbCVDMiVBMA/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB59f7f451" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here is a claim</a> that OpenAI=E2=
=80=99s <em>employees=C2=A0</em>get a capped profit interest instead of sto=
ck (or stock options, or restricted stock units), because of its nonprofit =
structure, and that this profit interest gets better=C2=A0<em>tax treatment=
</em>, for them, than standard startup equity awards:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People receiving profit interests will be gran=
ted the units upon their vesting date at no additional cost. Because of tha=
t, there=E2=80=99s an additional key tax benefit in that they are tax-free =
upon issuance and vesting, so the only tax hit would be a capital gains tax=
 when the profit is received or sold.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In contrast, with a traditional Restricted Sto=
ck Unit (RSU) that you=E2=80=99d see at a MAANG level company, when the RSU=
 vests, an employee will be taxed upon receiving their RSUs immediately. Th=
is is because the RSU is essentially a percentage of equity in the company =
and holds a value at whatever the market rate is for that company=E2=80=99s=
 stock.</p>
</blockquote>
