</em>trees reduces climate change, but you can=E2=80=99t get credit for jus=
t leaving existing trees alone.=E2=80=9D Another (far more common) way to t=
hink about trees is =E2=80=9Cthe trees store carbon, so leaving the trees a=
lone is carbon-reducing, so you can generate carbon credits by leaving tree=
s alone.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Perhaps the question is what process you are measuri=
ng: The process of =E2=80=9Cbeing a tree=E2=80=9D stores carbon and is good=
; the process of =E2=80=9Ccutting down trees=E2=80=9D releases carbon and i=
s bad.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When cows burp they release carbon. You might =
imagine saying =E2=80=9Ca cattle rancher with X cows generates Y tons of ca=
rbon emissions, and should have to buy carbon offsets to be neutral.=E2=80=
=9D Or: =E2=80=9CA cattle rancher with X cows, who changes their feed to a =
special low-burp diet, will only generate Z tons of carbon emissions (Z &lt=
; Y), so will have to buy fewer carbon offsets to be neutral.=E2=80=9D But =
it=E2=80=99s just a question of baselines. Why not: =E2=80=9CA=C2=A0cattle =
rancher with X cows, who changes their feed to a special low-burp diet, wil=
l only generate Z tons of carbon emissions (Z &lt; Y), and so will <em>redu=
ce</em> global emissions by (Z -=C2=A0X), and so will=C2=A0<em>generate=C2=
=A0</em>carbon credits that she can sell to airlines.=E2=80=9D And then the=
 airlines can burn a lot of jet fuel and put carbon into the atmosphere, an=
d they can say =E2=80=9Cbut it=E2=80=99s okay because we are paying some co=
ws to burp less.=E2=80=9D</p>
